{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 64, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 64 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 91, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 91 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 88, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 74, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 82, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 82 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'RTX12 T12', 'description': 'twenty patients with ra (17 women and 3 men, average age +/- sem: 52,6+/-3,8 years) were included in the study. All patients met the American College of Rheumatology classification criteria for the diagnosis of RA. All patients had active disease at the time of tissue sampling and were resistant to TNF blockade. They all had erosive changes imaged on conventional x-rays of the hands and/or feet. All of them had a swollen knee at inclusion. Rituximab therapy was administrated at a dose of 1,000 mg IV at baseline (T0) and at week 2, together with 125 mg IV Methylprednisolone. Clinical parameters at baseline (T0) and 12 weeks after the initiation of therapy (T12) was evaluated using DAS(28)-CRP scores and clinical responses were assessed using EULAR response criteria. Synovial biopsies were obtained by needle-arthroscopy of an affected knee from all patients at T0 and T12. For each procedure, 4 to 8 synovial samples were kept overnight at 4Â°C in a RNA stabilizing solution (RNALater, Ambion, Applied Biosystems, TX, USA) and then stored at â€“80Â°C for later RNA extraction. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. Synovial biopsies were obtained by needle-arthroscopy of an affected knee from all patients at T0 and T12. For each procedure, 4 to 8 synovial samples were kept overnight at 4Â°C in a RNA stabilizing solution (RNALater, Ambion, Applied Biosystems, TX, USA) and then stored at â€“80Â°C for later RNA extraction. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 4 from patient 43, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 43 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 49, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 49 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 69, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 43, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 46, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 46 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 31, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 31 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 75, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 45, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 45 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 25, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 25 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 64, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 4 from patient 26, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 26 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 80, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. 'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. Clinical parameters at baseline (T0) and 12 weeks after the initiation of therapy (T12) was evaluated using DAS(28)-CRP scores and clinical responses were assessed using EULAR response criteria. Synovial biopsies were obtained by needle-arthroscopy of an affected knee from all patients at T0 and T12. For each procedure, 4 to 8 synovial samples were kept overnight at 4Â°C in a RNA stabilizing solution (RNALater, Ambion, Applied Biosystems, TX, USA) and then stored at â€“80Â°C for later RNA extraction. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 28, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 28 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 55, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 55 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 73, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 36, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 42, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 42 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

All of them had a swollen knee at inclusion. Rituximab therapy was administrated at a dose of 1,000 mg IV at baseline (T0) and at week 2, together with 125 mg IV Methylprednisolone. Clinical parameters at baseline (T0) and 12 weeks after the initiation of therapy (T12) was evaluated using DAS(28)-CRP scores and clinical responses were assessed using EULAR response criteria. Synovial biopsies were obtained by needle-arthroscopy of an affected knee from all patients at T0 and T12. For each procedure, 4 to 8 synovial samples were kept overnight at 4Â°C in a RNA stabilizing solution (RNALater, Ambion, Applied Biosystems, TX, USA) and then stored at â€“80Â°C for later RNA extraction. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 4 from patient 32, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 32 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 49, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 49 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 62, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 62 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 31, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 8, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 45, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 45 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

All of them had a swollen knee at inclusion. Rituximab therapy was administrated at a dose of 1,000 mg IV at baseline (T0) and at week 2, together with 125 mg IV Methylprednisolone. Clinical parameters at baseline (T0) and 12 weeks after the initiation of therapy (T12) was evaluated using DAS(28)-CRP scores and clinical responses were assessed using EULAR response criteria. Synovial biopsies were obtained by needle-arthroscopy of an affected knee from all patients at T0 and T12. For each procedure, 4 to 8 synovial samples were kept overnight at 4Â°C in a RNA stabilizing solution (RNALater, Ambion, Applied Biosystems, TX, USA) and then stored at â€“80Â°C for later RNA extraction. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 68, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 65, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 65 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 3, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine.
