'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 71, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 32, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 32 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 47, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 47 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 21 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 44, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 44 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 4 from patient 2, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 2 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 52, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. 'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 66, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 66 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'RTX12 T0', 'description': 'twenty patients with ra (17 women and 3 men, average age +/- sem: 52,6+/-3,8 years) were included in the study. All patients met the American College of Rheumatology classification criteria for the diagnosis of RA. All patients had active disease at the time of tissue sampling and were resistant to TNF blockade. They all had erosive changes imaged on conventional x-rays of the hands and/or feet. All of them had a swollen knee at inclusion. Rituximab therapy was administrated at a dose of 1,000 mg IV at baseline (T0) and at week 2, together with 125 mg IV Methylprednisolone. Clinical parameters at baseline (T0) and 12 weeks after the initiation of therapy (T12) was evaluated using DAS(28)-CRP scores and clinical responses were assessed using EULAR response criteria. Synovial biopsies were obtained by needle-arthroscopy of an affected knee from all patients at T0 and T12. For each procedure, 4 to 8 synovial samples were kept overnight at 4Â°C in a RNA stabilizing solution (RNALater, Ambion, Applied Biosystems, TX, USA) and then stored at â€“80Â°C for later RNA extraction. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 26, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 4 from patient 17, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 17 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

All patients had active disease at the time of tissue sampling and were resistant to TNF blockade. They all had erosive changes imaged on conventional x-rays of the hands and/or feet. All of them had a swollen knee at inclusion. Rituximab therapy was administrated at a dose of 1,000 mg IV at baseline (T0) and at week 2, together with 125 mg IV Methylprednisolone. Clinical parameters at baseline (T0) and 12 weeks after the initiation of therapy (T12) was evaluated using DAS(28)-CRP scores and clinical responses were assessed using EULAR response criteria. Synovial biopsies were obtained by needle-arthroscopy of an affected knee from all patients at T0 and T12. For each procedure, 4 to 8 synovial samples were kept overnight at 4Â°C in a RNA stabilizing solution (RNALater, Ambion, Applied Biosystems, TX, USA) and then stored at â€“80Â°C for later RNA extraction. The same amount of tissue was snap-frozen in liquid nitrogen and kept at â€“80Â°C for immunostaining experiments on frozen sections. The remaining material was fixed in 10% formaldehyde and paraffin embedded for conventional optical evaluation and immunostaining of selected markers. All the experiments (RNA extraction, histology, immunohistochemistry) were performed on at least 4 biopsies harvested during every procedure in order to correct for variations related to the potential heterogeneous distribution of synovial inflammation. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 58, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 58 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 65, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 65 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 29, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 63, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 63 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 59, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 59 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 62, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 94, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 94 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 92, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 93, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 93 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 68, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 68 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 7, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 7 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 48, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 48 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 7, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 7 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 88, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 69, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 69 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 39, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 39 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 20, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 20 gingival tissue sample collected as Affected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Diseased (BoP + interproximal PPD of>3 mm + concomitant CAL of>2 mm);\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 9, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 3 from patient 37, Unaffected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected. This section comprised the ulcerated epithelial lining of the interproximal periodontal pockets and a portion of the underlying connective tissue.", 'type': 'RNA', 'source_name_ch1': 'Patient 37 gingival tissue sample collected as Unaffected', 'characteristics_ch1': 'Gingival tissue phenotype: Healthy (no BoP + PPD of<5 mm + CAL of<3 2 mm;\tTissue: Gingival'}

{'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 1 from patient 24, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Eligible patients were (i) at least 13 yr old; (ii) had a minimum of 24 teeth present; (iii) had no past history of systematic periodontal therapy other than occasional prophylaxis provided by the referring general dentist, (iv) had received no systemic antibiotics or anti-inflammatory drugs for at least 6 months, (v) harbored a minimum of 4 teeth with radiographic bone loss, (vi) did not suffer from diabetes mellitus, (vii) did not suffer from any of the systemic conditions or genetic disorders that entail a diagnosis of 'Periodontitis as a manifestation of systemic diseases', (viii) were not pregnant, and (ix) were not current users of tobacco products or of nicotine replacement medication. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. {'title': 'Gingival tissue sample 2 from patient 39, Affected site', 'description': "A total of 90 subjects with moderate to severe periodontitis (63 with chronic and 27 with aggressive periodontitis) were recruited among the patients referred for periodontal therapy to the Clinic for Post-doctoral Periodontics, Columbia University College of Dental Medicine. Signed informed consent was obtained prior to enrollment. All participants underwent a full-mouth examination of the periodontal tissues at six sites per tooth, using a manual probe. The examination included assessments of presence/absence of dental plaque and bleeding on probing (BoP), and linear measurements of probing pocket depth (PPD) and clinical attachment level (CAL).  'Diseased' sites showed BoP, had an interproximal PPD of>3 mm, and a concomitant CAL of>2 mm. 'Healthy' sites showed no BoP, had PPD of<5 mm and CAL of<3 mm. A software program identified (i) maxillary 'diseased' and 'healthy' interdental papillae, based on the above criteria and (ii) pairs of diseased interdental papillae with similar clinical presentation, i.e., with PPD and CAL within 2 mm of each other. A posterior maxillary sextant encompassing a pair of qualifying 'diseased' interdental papillae was identified.  Periodontal surgery was performed at the identified sextant without any prior supra- or subgingival instrumentation. After infiltration with an appropriate local anesthetic, submarginal incisions were performed, mucoperiosteal flaps were reflected, and the portion of each interproximal gingival papilla that adhered to the root surface was carefully dissected.
